<text>Heat Propagation

By Bob Tinker

What causes heat to propagate? How fast does it propagate? 

   
 

Further experiments:

Shock waves. Cool the entire crystal until every atom is black. Now hit one end with ten clicks with the heating tool and run. Sometimes you can see a shockwave going through the crystal. This is not normal thermal propagation. 
     
Thermal memory. Cool the crystal until it is black. Stop it and select the move tool to reset the recorder. Heat the 
center with ten clicks of the heat tool. Run the model for 20 cycles and stop. Remove all the heat so every atom is black. Not how the crystal has changed shape. What do you see? Now run the model again. What do you see? Why did it heat up again? Repeat stopping the model, removing the heat, and then running again. What is happening? 

Effect of defects. Real substances are not single crystals. Rearrange the atoms to make multiple crystals and observe the effect of grain boundaries. Here is a model that has two crystals.    </text>
